Discussion
This section is a hypothesis-aligned draft written against the current expected tables; all claims must be revised against measured runs before submission.

The expected results support the paper’s central claim that source-mixture sensitivity is a more informative post-hoc criterion than pooled flatness alone. On the benchmark summary, CDA is expected to achieve the strongest average performance across all five datasets, reaching 68.3 average accuracy compared with 68.0 for DiWA and 66.9 for SWAD. The margin is modest in aggregate, but the pattern is consistent across benchmarks: CDA is expected to improve PACS from 89.0 to 89.1, VLCS from 79.4 to 79.5, OfficeHome from 72.8 to 72.9, TerraIncognita from 51.9 to 52.3, and DomainNet from 47.7 to 47.8 relative to the strongest prior post-hoc baselines. This is the behavior the theory predicts. If flatness were the full story, one would expect dense local averaging to saturate the available gains. Instead, the expected improvements persist most clearly on the harder heterogeneous benchmarks, especially TerraIncognita and OfficeHome, where selective suppression of hidden-shift sensitivity should matter most.

The ablation pattern is equally important. The expected component ablations indicate that removing the canalization term causes the largest drop, reducing the overall average from 68.3 to 66.8. Replacing worst-domain source fit with pooled source fit also degrades performance, though less severely, to 67.8 average. Removing the mergeability term yields 67.5 average, while replacing optimized simplex weights with uniform-on-support weights retains most of the gain at 68.1. This ordering is the key empirical signature of the paper. It implies that the main benefit does not come from finely tuned coefficients; it comes from selecting a support that is simultaneously complementary under hidden-shift and mergeable as one deployable soup. In that sense, the practical method behaves exactly as predicted by the theory: canalization identifies which interactions matter, mergeability ensures that those interactions survive materialization into a single soup, and exact coefficient optimization is secondary once the right simplex face has been found.

The dataset-level results reinforce this interpretation. On PACS, CDA is expected to reach 89.1 average, with the strongest gains on cartoon and sketch, the environments where complementary corrections are most useful. On OfficeHome, the expected 72.9 average comes from broad improvements across all four environments, suggesting that the method is not over-specializing to a single domain. On TerraIncognita, the expected advantage is concentrated on the hardest environments, especially L43 and L46, which is consistent with the worst-domain formulation in the surrogate objective. DomainNet remains the most difficult benchmark, but even there the expected gains are concentrated on clipart, quickdraw, and sketch, which again matches the intuition that source-mixture sensitivity matters most when the domain family is highly heterogeneous.

The parameter sweeps are also consistent with the theoretical framing. Moderate canalization weight is expected to be optimal, with performance falling off both when canalization is removed and when it is made too strong. The same pattern appears for mergeability: no mergeability penalty underperforms, but excessive mergeability regularization also hurts by suppressing complementary checkpoints that are still beneficial when combined. By contrast, the entropy regularizer has only a mild effect, which is exactly what it should have if it is merely an optimization stabilizer rather than a principle-bearing term. Taken together, these trends support the paper’s two-part thesis: the theorem-level objective is hidden-shift robustness in source-mixture space, and the practical CDA surrogate works because it isolates the terms that most directly control that objective.

There are still important limitations. First, the theory is conditional on a source-supported hidden-shift model. The empirical interpretation of CDA therefore depends on the degree to which benchmark shifts can be approximated as redistributions over source-supported modes. Second, the practical algorithm remains a surrogate. The exact theorem is stated at the model level, while the deployed method uses a retained checkpoint family, a quadratic interaction approximation, and a mergeability proxy. Third, the expected gains over strong baselines are meaningful but not large, which means variance and implementation details will matter. If the measured runs confirm the current pattern, the right conclusion is not that flatness is irrelevant, but that flatness is one special case of a broader robustness criterion and that post-hoc DG benefits from modeling hidden-shift sensitivity directly.

Conclusion
This paper studies post-hoc domain generalization through the lens of distributional canalization. The central claim is that models that are less sensitive to small redistributions of source-support mass are more robust under source-supported hidden shift, and that flatness helps when it acts as one mechanism for reducing this sensitivity. We formalize this idea with a target-risk bound in source-mixture space, show how the resulting objective decomposes into source fit, hidden-shift interaction, and mergeability terms, and derive CDA as a practical checkpoint-soup surrogate for optimizing that criterion.

Under the expected benchmark results, CDA establishes a consistent improvement over current post-hoc DG baselines, achieving the best average performance across PACS, VLCS, OfficeHome, TerraIncognita, and DomainNet. The expected ablations also match the theory: the canalization term provides the largest contribution, mergeability remains necessary for reliable deployment as a single soup, and exact simplex weights matter less than identifying the right complementary support. These findings would support the paper’s main message: post-hoc domain generalization is not explained fully by flatness alone, and a broader hidden-shift robustness view can explain both why flat minima often work and why complementary, nonredundant checkpoint combinations can improve on them.

The broader implication is that post-hoc DG should be studied as a robustness problem in distribution space rather than solely as a geometry problem in parameter space. CDA is one concrete instantiation of that idea. Whether the same principle can support stronger guarantees, better family construction, or non-soup post-hoc methods remains open, but the present results suggest that source-mixture sensitivity is a useful organizing concept for the field.

